## Overview

The WebSocket API is an advanced technology that makes it possible to open a two-way interactive communication session between a client and a server. With this API, you can send messages to a server and receive event-driven responses without having to poll the server for a reply.

Please note that all unauthenticated WebSocket connections are automatically closed after 15 minutes regardless of activity.

You can read more about WebSockets [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WebSockets_API).

---

## Connection

### URL

Our WebSocket API is accessible on the following address:

<a href="null">wss://api.valr.com</a>

- **Account WebSocket connection**: In order to receive streaming updates about your VALR account, you would open up a WebSocket connection to

    <a href="null">wss://api.valr.com/ws/account</a>

- **Trade WebSocket connection**: In order to receive streaming updates about Trade data, you would open up a WebSocket connection to

    <a href="null">wss://api.valr.com/ws/trade</a>


### Connecting using NodeJS

There are various WebSocket libraries that one can use to interact with our WebSocket API, depending on your choice of programming language and development framework. In NodeJS, you can use a popular library called [ws](https://github.com/websockets/ws) for authentication, establishing a connection and to receive live updates.

You can use the following command to install the `ws` package to your NodeJS project:

`npm install ws`

Once `ws` is installed, you can authenticate and establish a connection to our API with the following code:

``` javascript
const WebSocket = require('ws')
var headers = getAuthHeaders('/ws/account')
// Authenticate and establish a connection
const ws = new WebSocket('wss://api.valr.com/ws/account', { headers })
ws.on('open', () =>  {
    // you can now start working with the connection
})
ws.on('message', data =>  {
    // work with data
})
ws.on('error', err => {
    // handle error
})
ws.on('close', () => {
    // reconnect if needed
})

 ```

Once authenticated, and the connection is established, the code above listens to the `open`, `message`, `error` and `close` events emitted from the server. The relevant payload will be available for each of these events. The one that is most interesting is the `data` payload on the `message` event. You will make use of this payload when receiving and working with live message updates.

---

## Authentication

Our WebSocket API requires authentication. To authenticate, add the following headers to the first call that establishes the WebSocket connection.

- **X-VALR-API-KEY**: Your API Key

- **X-VALR-SIGNATURE**: Generated signature. The signature is generated using the following parameters:

    - Api Secret

    - Timestamp of request

    - HTTP verb 'GET'

    - Path (either `/ws/account` or `/ws/trade`)

    - Request Body should be empty

- **X-VALR-TIMESTAMP**: Timestamp of the request


Like this for `Account` WebSocket (in NodeJS):

`const ws = new WebSocket('wss://api.valr.com/ws/account', { headers })`

Or, if you want to connect to the `Trade` WebSocket, you would use the appropriate path:

`const ws = new WebSocket('wss://api.valr.com/ws/trade', { headers })`

The headers that are passed to establish the connection are the same 3 headers you pass to any authenticated call to the REST API. Here's how you would populate these headers:

``` javascript
function getAuthHeaders(path) {
    var headers = new Object()
    var timestamp = (new Date()).getTime()
    var signature = signRequest(apiKeySecret, timestamp, 'GET', path, '')
    headers['X-VALR-API-KEY'] = apiKey
    headers["X-VALR-SIGNATURE"] = signature
    headers['X-VALR-TIMESTAMP'] = timestamp
    return headers
}

 ```

The `signRequest` method is repeated below for your convenience:

``` javascript
const crypto = require("crypto")
function signRequest(apiKeySecret, timestamp, verb, path, body = "") {
  return crypto
    .createHmac("sha512", apiKeySecret)
    .update(timestamp.toString())
    .update(verb.toUpperCase())
    .update(path)
    .update(body)
    .digest("hex")
}

 ```

The `signRequest` method requires the `crypto` package. You can use the following command to install the `crypto` package to your NodeJS project:

`npm install crypto`

### Putting it all together

In NodeJS, your code to establish an authenticated connection to our WebSocket API and start listening to message feeds would look like this:

``` javascript
const crypto = require("crypto")
const WebSocket = require("ws")
const apiKey = "yourapikey"
const apiKeySecret = "yourapikeysecret"
function signRequest(apiKeySecret, timestamp, verb, path, body = "") {
  return crypto
    .createHmac("sha512", apiKeySecret)
    .update(timestamp.toString())
    .update(verb.toUpperCase())
    .update(path)
    .update(body)
    .digest("hex")
}
function getAuthHeaders(path) {
  var headers = new Object()
  var timestamp = new Date().getTime()
  var signature = signRequest(apiKeySecret, timestamp, "GET", path, "")
  headers["X-VALR-API-KEY"] = apiKey
  headers["X-VALR-SIGNATURE"] = signature
  headers["X-VALR-TIMESTAMP"] = timestamp
  return headers
}
// Account WebSocket connection
function connectToAccount() {
    var headers = getAuthHeaders('/ws/account')
    const wsAccount = new WebSocket('wss://api.valr.com/ws/account', { headers })
    wsAccount.on("open", () => {
        // you can now start working with the connection
        console.log("Account WS connected");
    })
    wsAccount.on("message", data => {
        // work with data
    })
    wsAccount.on("error", err => {
        // handle error
    })
    wsAccount.on("close", () => {
        // reconnect if needed
    })
}
// Trade WebSocket connection
function connectToTrade() {
    var headers = getAuthHeaders("/ws/trade")
    const wsTrade = new WebSocket('wss://api.valr.com/ws/trade', { headers })
    wsTrade.on("open", () => {
      // you can now start working with the connection
      console.log('Trade WS connected')
    })
    wsTrade.on("message", data => {
      // work with data
    })
    wsTrade.on("error", err => {
      // handle error
    })
    wsTrade.on("close", () => {
      // reconnect if needed
    })
}
connectToAccount()
connectToTrade()

